      <memberdef kind="variable" id="classMR_1_1EmbeddedPython_1a14bbe74feab93ace0f4c09eab821a9ce" prot="private" static="no" mutable="no">
        <type>std::thread</type>
        <definition>std::thread MR::EmbeddedPython::interpreterThread_</definition>
        <argsstring></argsstring>
        <name>interpreterThread_</name>
        <qualifiedname>MR::EmbeddedPython::interpreterThread_</qualifiedname>
        <briefdescription>
<para>It&apos;s could (?) be more efficient to have more CVs here, but one is simpler. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>We maintain ONE persistent thread that runs all python scripts, and persists while the program runs. This seems to be the safest option, I had issues otherwise. We need everything Python-related to happen in the same thread, and we also need to not finalize-and-recreate the interpreter while the program runs because that breaks our generated bindings (which may or may not be possible to fix in the bindings, but it&apos;s easier not to, and the manual even advises that some modules can break if you recreate the interpreter: <ulink url="https:///">https:///</ulink> docs.python.org/3/c-api/init.html::c.Py_FinalizeEx). </para>
        </detaileddescription>
        <inbodydescription>
        </inbodydescription>
        <location file="/home/runner/work/MeshLib/MeshLib/MeshLib/source/MREmbeddedPython/MREmbeddedPython.h" line="79" column="17" bodyfile="/home/runner/work/MeshLib/MeshLib/MeshLib/source/MREmbeddedPython/MREmbeddedPython.h" bodystart="79" bodyend="-1"/>
      </memberdef>
